The TEM images of CDs revealed the spherical morphology, amorphous nature and dispersibility with an average size of 7.7 nm as shown in the size distribution diagram (Fig. 3
                        ). The EDX (Energy Dispersive X-ray Analysis) spectrum showed the presence of carbon and oxygen with atomic percentages 94.7 and 3.8%, respectively (Fig. S1). The XRD spectrum exhibited a broad peak around 20.7° which demonstrates the amorphous nature and presence of disordered carbon atoms (Zhou et al., 2013) (Fig. 4
                        a). To determine the surface charge, the zeta potential of CDs, also described as the electrokinetic potential, was measured using a zeta-sizer and was found to be −11.2 mV (Fig. 4b). This method additionally elucidates certain features such as stability and presence of functional groups (hydroxyl, carboxyl, and carbonyl). The duration of time a fluorophore remains in the excited state before emitting a photon and returning back to the ground state is known as the fluorescence lifetime. The fluorescence lifetime fluctuates whenever the fluorophore's physicochemical environment changes. It is a characteristic feature of fluorescent substances and a crucial variable in applications involving sensing. Fluorescence lifetime analysis have also been done and was found to be 21 ns (Fig. S2).
